David: Hey guys, let’s divide this up into sections. We should divide it by sections 1 and 2, 3 and 4, 5 and 6, 7-9. Does this sound OK?

3.0 Current situation and problem/opportunity statement
For our project we still need to build a web page for it to run. We will be using Google’s free web spaces. 

4.0 Critical assumptions and constraints

5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation

During a brainstorm session, multiple options arose to satisfy the objective:
Create a presentation on technical failures such as those featured on old movies.
A website was also considered for this option.
Create a website for an on-campus organization.
Create a website with mini games exploiting the new HTML5 standards.
Create a web-based alternate reality scavenger hunt game.
Ultimately, the team decided to proceed with option 4 as it is an interesting concept and has not been explored to a large extent.

6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements

The main features of the web-based alternate reality scavenger hunt game will include the following:
A landing page with a brief description of the game, and an opportunity to log-in or register an account. The account will simply be the name and e-mail address of a player.
The current puzzle will be displayed upon log-in. The puzzle will be presented in a one-page interface with an input area included to submit a solution to the puzzle.
A leaderboard page with the current rankings and progress of each user.
A back-end interface for changing the current puzzle. A puzzle may include both an image and text.
The back-end interface should send an e-mail out to all users to notify them of a new puzzle.
Other features determined by the team or users as development progresses.

7.0 Budget Estimates and Financial Analysis

A preliminary estimates of costs for the entire project is $50. This estimate is based on the prizes that the user/participant will win upon successfully completion of the provided clues information. The developers and the project manager will not be paid for the amount of work they provide. Other resources that will be used to complete this project will be open source software that does not require any money to successfully complete this project. Furthermore, the project will utilize Google App Engine’s free tier.

	Projected benefits are based on researching project management information, appropriate tools, templates and similar competing application. Projected benefits also include increased number of users/participants. If one user suggests the web based application to another person through word of mouth the estimated number of people involved will be 40 people within a 4 week time period.

8.0 Schedule Estimate

	The team would like to see the project completed within 7 weeks, but there is flexibility in the schedule. We also assume that the new system will have a useful life of at least six months.

9.0 Potential Risks

There are several risks involved with this project. The foremost risk is the time period for this project. With the time period estimated and the complexity of this project, the developers might have to go over the time period by a week. User participation of this project is important to this application in realizing the potential benefits from using this application. There is also some technical risks of using Google engine as our development tool. Since every developer is not very familiar with this tool, some unforeseen technical difficulties might arise that might be challenging to resolve. The main business risk is investing the time and energy into this project and not realizing the projected benefits.

1.0 Introduction/background

	The Green LanTeam is a project group that was created to make a project about information systems. The four members in our group will collaborate together to come up with a project that is complicated enough to carry out in 3 months. We will use our various skills and knowledge to generate a great project.

2.0 Business objective

	For our project we want to create a reality-based adventure game, where participants need to find the clues in buildings around the campus, after solving that puzzle they will input their answer on our website, the first person who correctly answers the challenge will receive a reward. We will give out challenges through a website, and we will be running simple applications to handle the actions. Our goal is to provide campus students with some fun for solving our puzzles. We also want to get students to know the campus better through going to different buildings on campus.

3.0 Current situation and problem/opportunity statement

For our project we still need to build a web page for it to run. We will be using Google App for running our program.  We may need to purchase a domain for our website because if we use Google’s given domain it may be too long for people to remember. Another problem we are having is to gain visitors and make the game interesting enough for them to play. Since it’s reality-based some people may find it difficult to walk around buildings on campus to find clues for the game, therefore we need to have some incentives to attract them to play. If our website receives many attentions we can take the opportunity to extend our project to over the quarter. 

4.0 Critical assumptions and constraints

The website is assumed to have a decent amount of visitors everyday for our puzzles. If our puzzle attracts college students then we will have more visits from their friends and families. Our puzzle is a one-time only game, the first person who finds the puzzle will take the clue will give in answers on our website. Therefore, we need to constantly add new challenges throughout the quarter to ensure we always have interesting puzzles for our visitors. In addition, our program will be web-based so we will not have many dynamic features such as real-time interactions with the users and so on.
